postcontent: For Sale: Pioneer Arms Corp Inter Ordnance PPS43cCaliber: 7.62x25mm TokarevPrice: $500.00Barrel Length: 9.5” Add Ons: (4) 35 Round Magazines, Cleaning Rod and Oil that came with it new, soft case, Approximately 390 Rounds, Special Note: The stock is welded in place per ATF rules so it does not become a SBRFace to Face Sales in Montana only. $500 Firm. No Trades.Polish PPS-43C semi auto pistolThe History...The PPS-43C (Pistolet-Pulemet Sudaeva, model of 1943 = Sudaev SMG) was born as an answer to the need for a weapon that is more compact and mobile than the PPSh-41, then in use by the Soviet Army. The PPSh-41 was somewhat too long to be used by tank crews and mobile recon groups and paratroopers, so late in 1941, the Red Army issued a request for a new more compact sub machine gun (SMG). The designer Sudaev initially designed his new SMG in 1942, and it was adopted under the designation of PPS-42. The next year he refined the design, and this final model was designated as the PPS-43. This model was manufactured in significant numbers (nearly two million PPS-43 weapons were manufactured between 1943 and 1946). The PPS-43 is sometimes referred to as the best SMG of World War II. After WWII, it was widely exported to pro-Soviet regimes around the world, and widely copied.

title: For Sale:  In Graham: Taurus Thunderbolt .357/38Spcl Pump Rifle
postcontent: In Graham: Runs flawlessly, all of the time. Beautiful in every way. Nearly one of a kind, I can't find another one of this caliber (.357/38spcl...it shoots both from the same chamber and is stamped for both) anywhere.Never intended to sell but need the cash, moving.This is a Taurus Thunderbolt long barrel rifle. It is designed after the Colt Lightning rifle, and Taurus only made a few in this caliber.Taurus Thunderbolt rifles were produced for a very short time and they were all in the caliber of 45LC. They promised the .357/.38 Spcl model to soon come but then, to the world's disappointment, advertised they were not going to manufacture that model. Somewhere in the last minute of making this gun, they ran a few...very few.The 45LC models had a problem, they were not always extracting properly because that .45 had nearly no rim on it(you can read all about it on the internet)..that is probably why Taurus halted expanding the model, but the .357 and .38 special round has a perfect rim for extracting and the few that they made, run absolutely perfect.I have no idea why they didn't take off with that model once they learned it was a winner. Maybe they were committed to moving to the next run of something else. Anyway, the bluing is so dark it looks almost Parkerized, but it is certainly just quality bluing, it is a Cadillac of a finish. The hard wood furniture is stained so dark it is almost black...very nice.It is heavy, supremely built and has a glass like finish with equally impressive lines.The recoil is almost zero. It has zero malfunctions and is near perfect in every way.Has a Skinner Peep sight and stacks bulets nearly on top of each  other at 35 yards. You cannot be disappointed if you.end up with this.I will be, but you won't.
